\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\kerning0\b Basic LINUX Commands:-\par
1. ls => shows different options\b0\par
              -->ls -a => include hidden file\par
              -->ls -l => long listing format -> its shows created date, changed date, bytes\par
              -->ls -t (sort by last modified file)\par
              -->ls -s (sort by file size)\ul\par
file  permission:-\par
\ulnone d                               r w x       r w x       r w x          \par
directory               r- read, w-write, x - execute\par
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\par
\b 2.pwd \b0\par
-shows which directory we are in ie., present working directory\par
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\par
\b 3. cd Desktop\b0\par
-it change the directory as desktop\par
--> cd ..\par
-to come back to home directory\par
-->cd Videos--> relative path\par
-->cd /home/rps/Videos -->Absolute path\par
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\par
\b 4.mkdir directory_name\b0\par
-->mkdir batch2  or mkdir /home/rps/Videos\par
-Adding new directory (make new directory)\par
-It can be one or more directory created ==> mkdir folder1 folder2 folder3\par
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\b\par
5.rmdir directory_name\par
\b0 -Remove the directory\par
-it can be one or multiple directory ==> rmdir folfer1 folder2 folder3\par
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\par
\b 6. touch\b0\par
-It can be used to create a new file\par
==> touch file_name,  \par
              eg:- touch file1\par
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\par
\b 7.rm \b0\par
-it is used to remove the already created file\par
== > rm file_name, \par
        eg:- rm file1 file2\par
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\par
\b 8. cat\b0\par
-Used to view the content of the file\par
==>cat file_name.\par
        eg:- cat notes.txt\par
-Create a file content\par
==> cat > file_name\par
         eg:- touch file1.txt\par
                 cat >\par
                  Welcome you all!\par
                  Hello world\par
                  ctrl+d to exit the edit content\par
                  cat file1.txt\par
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\kerning2\par

